	Customs officers
		The Treasury may by order provide for any provision of this Part which appliesin relation to police officers or persons arrested by police officers to applywith specified modifications in relation to customs officers or personsarrested by customs officers.
	Service policemen
		The Secretary of State may by order provide for any provision of this Partwhich applies in relation to police officers or persons arrested by policeofficers to apply with specified modifications in relation to servicepolicemen or persons arrested by service policemen.

British overseas territories
	Extradition from British overseas territories
		This section applies in relation to extradition—
			from a British overseas territory to a category 1 territory;
			from a British overseas territory to the United Kingdom;
			from a British overseas territory to a category 2 territory;
			from a British overseas territory to any of the Channel Islands or the Isleof Man.
		An Order in Council may provide for any provision of this Act applicable toextradition from the United Kingdom to apply to extradition in a case fallingwithin subsection (1)(a) or (b).
		An Order in Council may provide for any provision of this Act applicable toextradition from the United Kingdom to a category 2 territory to apply toextradition in a case falling within subsection (1)(c) or (d).
		An Order in Council under this section may provide that the provisionapplied has effect with specified modifications.
	Extradition to British overseas territories
		This section applies in relation to extradition—
			to a British overseas territory from a category 1 territory;
			to a British overseas territory from the United Kingdom;
			to a British overseas territory from a category 2 territory;
			to a British overseas territory from any of the Channel Islands or the Isleof Man.
		An Order in Council may provide for any provision of this Act applicable toextradition to the United Kingdom to apply to extradition in a case fallingwithin subsection (1)(a) or (b).
		An Order in Council may provide for any provision of this Act applicable toextradition to the United Kingdom from a category 2 territory to apply toextradition in a case falling within subsection (1)(c) or (d).
		An Order in Council under this section may provide that the provisionapplied has effect with specified modifications.

Genocide etc
	Genocide, crimes against humanity and war crimes
		This section applies if—
			a Part 1 warrant in respect of a person is issued in respect of an offencementioned in subsection (2), or
			a valid request for a person’s extradition is made in respect of an offencementioned in subsection (2).
		The offences are—
			an offence that if committed in the United Kingdom would be punishable asan offence under section 51 or 58 of the International Criminal Court Act[2001 (c. 17)](/id/ukpga/2001/17?view=plain "Go to item of legislation")(genocide, crimes against humanity and war crimes);
			an offence that if committed in the United Kingdom would be punishable asan offence under section 52 or 59 of that Act (conduct ancillary to genocide,etc. committed outside the jurisdiction);
			an offence that if committed in the United Kingdom would be punishable asan ancillary offence, as defined in section 55 or 62 of that Act, in relationto an offence falling within paragraph (a) or (b);
			an offence that if committed in the United Kingdom would be punishable asan offence under section 1 of the International Criminal Court (Scotland) Act[2001 (asp 13)](/id/asp/2001/13?view=plain "Go to item of legislation")(genocide, crimes against humanity and war crimes);
			an offence that if committed in the United Kingdom would be punishable asan offence under section 2 of that Act (conduct ancillary to genocide etc.committed outside the jurisdiction);
			an offence that if committed in the United Kingdom would be punishable asan ancillary offence, as defined in section 7 of that Act, in relation to anoffence falling within paragraph (d) or (e);
			any offence punishable in the United Kingdom under section 1 of the GenevaConventions Act [1957 (c. 52)](/id/ukpga/1957/52?view=plain "Go to item oflegislation") (grave breach of scheduled conventions).
		It is not an objection to extradition under this Act that the person couldnot have been punished for the offence under the law in force at the time whenand in the place where he is alleged to have committed the act of which he isaccused or of which he has been convicted.

Other miscellaneous provisions
	Extradition for more than one offence
		The Secretary of State may by order provide for this Act to have effect withspecified modifications in relation to a case where—
			a Part 1 warrant is issued in respect of more than one offence;
			a request for extradition is made in respect of more than one offence.
	National security
		This section applies if the Secretary of State believes that the conditionsin subsections (2) to (4) are satisfied in relation to a person.
		The first condition is that the person’s extradition is sought or will besought under Part 1 or Part 2 in respect of an offence.
		The second condition is that—
			in engaging in the conduct constituting (or alleged to constitute) theoffence the person was acting for the purpose of assisting in the exercise ofa function conferred or imposed by or under an enactment, or
			as a result of an authorisation given by the Secretary of State the personis not liable under the criminal law of any part of the United Kingdom for theconduct constituting (or alleged to constitute) the offence.
		The third condition is that the person’s extradition in respect of theoffence would be against the interests of national security.
		The Secretary of State may certify that the conditions in subsections (2)to (4) are satisfied in relation to the person.
		If the Secretary of State issues a certificate under subsection (5) he may—
			direct that a Part 1 warrant issued in respect of the person and in respectof the offence is not to be proceeded with, or
			direct that a request for the person’s extradition in respect of theoffence is not to be proceeded with.
		If the Secretary of State issues a certificate under subsection (5) he mayorder the person’s discharge (instead of or in addition to giving a directionunder subsection (6)).
		These rules apply if the Secretary of State gives a direction undersubsection (6)(a) in respect of a warrant—
			if the designated authority has not issued a certificate under section 2 inrespect of the warrant it must not do so;
			if the person is arrested under the warrant or under section 5 there is norequirement for him to be brought before the appropriate judge and he must bedischarged;
			if the person is brought before the appropriate judge under section 4 or 6the judge is no longer required to proceed or continue proceeding undersections 7 and 8;
			if the extradition hearing has begun the judge is no longer required toproceed or continue proceeding under sections 10 to 25;
			if the person has consented to his extradition, the judge is no longerrequired to order his extradition;
			if an appeal to the High Court or House of Lords has been brought, thecourt is no longer required to hear or continue hearing the appeal;
			if the person’s extradition has been ordered there is no requirement forhim to be extradited.
		These rules apply if the Secretary of State gives a direction undersubsection (6)(b) in respect of a request—
			if he has not issued a certificate under section 70 in respect of therequest he is no longer required to do so;
			if the person is arrested under a warrant issued under section 71 or undera provisional warrant there is no requirement for him to appear or be broughtbefore the appropriate judge and he must be discharged;
			if the person appears or is brought before the appropriate judge the judgeis no longer required to proceed or continue proceeding under sections 72, 74,75 and 76;
			if the extradition hearing has begun the judge is no longer required toproceed or continue proceeding under sections 78 to 91;
			if the person has given his consent to his extradition to the appropriatejudge, the judge is no longer required to send the case to the Secretary ofState for his decision whether the person is to be extradited;
			if an appeal to the High Court or House of Lords has been brought, thecourt is no longer required to hear or continue hearing the appeal;
			if the person’s extradition has been ordered there is no requirement forhim to be extradited.
		These must be made under the hand of the Secretary of State—
			a certificate under subsection (5);
			a direction under subsection (6);
			an order under subsection (7).
		The preceding provisions of this section apply to Scotland with thesemodifications—
			in subsection (9)(a) for “he has” substitute “the Scottish Ministers have”and for “he is” substitute “they are”;
			in subsection (9)(e) for “Secretary of State for his” substitute “ScottishMinisters for their”.
		In subsection (3) the reference to an enactment includes an enactmentcomprised in, or in an instrument made under, an Act of the ScottishParliament.
	Reasonable force
		A person may use reasonable force, if necessary, in the exercise of a powerconferred by this Act.
	Rules of court
		Rules of court may make provision as to the practice and procedure to befollowed in connection with proceedings under this Act.
		In Scotland any rules of court under this Act are to be made by Act ofAdjournal.
	Service of notices
		Service of a notice on a person under section 54, 56, 58, 129, 130 or 131 maybe effected in any of these ways—
			by delivering the notice to the person;
			by leaving it for him with another person at his last known or usual placeof abode;
			by sending it by post in a letter addressed to him at his last known orusual place of abode.
	Article 95 alerts: transitional provision
		This section applies in a case where an article 95 alert is issued before 1January 2004 by an authority of a category 1 territory.
		In such a case, this Act applies as if—
			the alert were a Part 1 warrant issued by the authority;
			any information sent with the alert relating to the case were included inthe warrant.
		As applied by subsection (2), this Act has effect with these modifications—
			in sections 2(7) and (8), 28(1), 30(1) and (4)(d), 32(2)(b), 33(6)(b),35(4)(b), 36(3)(b), 47(3)(b), 49(3)(b), 190(3) and 191(2)(a) for “authoritywhich issued the Part 1 warrant” substitute “authority at the request of whichthe alert was issued”;
			omit section 5;
			in sections 33(4)(b), 42(2)(a), 43(2)(a) and (4) and 61(1)(d) and (e), for“authority which issued the warrant” substitute “authority at the request ofwhich the alert was issued”;
			in section 66(2), for the words from “believes” to the end substitute“believes is the authority at the request of which the alert was issued”.
		An article 95 alert is an alert issued pursuant to article 95 of theConvention implementing the Schengen agreement of 14th June 1985.

Interpretation
	Disposal of Part 1 warrant and extradition request
		A Part 1 warrant issued in respect of a person is disposed of—
			when an order is made for the person’s discharge in respect of the warrantand there is no further possibility of an appeal;
			when the person is taken to be discharged in respect of the warrant;
			when an order is made for the person’s extradition in pursuance of thewarrant and there is no further possibility of an appeal.
		A request for a person’s extradition is disposed of—
			when an order is made for the person’s discharge in respect of the requestand there is no further possibility of an appeal;
			when the person is taken to be discharged in respect of the request;
			when an order is made for the person’s extradition in pursuance of therequest and there is no further possibility of an appeal.
		There is no further possibility of an appeal against an order for aperson’s discharge or extradition—
			when the period permitted for giving notice of an appeal to the High Courtends, if notice is not given before the end of that period;
			when the decision of the High Court on an appeal becomes final, if there isno appeal to the House of Lords against that decision;
			when the decision of the House of Lords on an appeal is made, if there issuch an appeal.
		The decision of the High Court on an appeal becomes final—
			when the period permitted for applying to the High Court for leave toappeal to the House of Lords ends, if there is no such application;
			when the period permitted for applying to the House of Lords for leave toappeal to it ends, if the High Court refuses leave to appeal and there is noapplication to the House of Lords for leave to appeal;
			when the House of Lords refuses leave to appeal to it;
			at the end of the permitted period, which is 28 days starting with the dayon which leave to appeal to the House of Lords is granted, if no such appealis brought before the end of that period.
		These must be ignored for the purposes of subsections (3) and (4)—
			any power of a court to extend the period permitted for giving notice ofappeal or for applying for leave to appeal;
			any power of a court to grant leave to take a step out of time.
		Subsections (3) to (5) do not apply to Scotland.
	Disposal of charge
		A charge against a person is disposed of—
			if the person is acquitted in respect of it, when he is acquitted;
			if the person is convicted in respect of it, when there is no furtherpossibility of an appeal against the conviction.
		There is no further possibility of an appeal against a conviction—
			when the period permitted for giving notice of application for leave toappeal to the Court of Appeal against the conviction ends, if the leave of theCourt of Appeal is required and no such notice is given before the end of thatperiod;
			when the Court of Appeal refuses leave to appeal against the conviction, ifthe leave of the Court of Appeal is required and notice of application forleave is given before the end of that period;
			when the period permitted for giving notice of appeal to the Court ofAppeal against the conviction ends, if notice is not given before the end ofthat period;
			when the decision of the Court of Appeal on an appeal becomes final, ifthere is no appeal to the House of Lords against that decision;
			when the decision of the House of Lords on an appeal is made, if there issuch an appeal.
		The decision of the Court of Appeal on an appeal becomes final—
			when the period permitted for applying to the Court of Appeal for leave toappeal to the House of Lords ends, if there is no such application;
			when the period permitted for applying to the House of Lords for leave toappeal to it ends, if the Court of Appeal refuses leave to appeal and there isno application to the House of Lords for leave to appeal;
			when the House of Lords refuses leave to appeal to it;
			at the end of the permitted period, which is 28 days starting with the dayon which leave to appeal to the House of Lords is granted, if no such appealis brought before the end of that period.
		These must be ignored for the purposes of subsections (2) and (3)—
			any power of a court to extend the period permitted for giving notice ofappeal or of application for leave to appeal or for applying for leave toappeal;
			any power of a court to grant leave to take a step out of time.
		Subsections (2) to (4) do not apply to Scotland.
	European framework list
		The European framework list is the list of conduct set out in Schedule 2.
		The Secretary of State may by order amend Schedule 2 for the purpose ofensuring that the list of conduct set out in the Schedule corresponds to thelist of conduct set out in article 2.2 of the European framework decision.
		The European framework decision is the framework decision of the Council ofthe European Union made on 13 June 2002 on the European arrest warrant and thesurrender procedures between member states (2002/584/JHA).
	Other interpretative provisions
		References to a category 1 territory must be read in accordance withsection 1.
		References to a category 2 territory must be read in accordance withsection 69.
		References to the designated authority must be read in accordance withsection 2(9).
		References to a Part 1 warrant must be read in accordance with section 2.
		References to a Part 3 warrant must be read in accordance with section 142.
		References to a valid request for a person’s extradition must be read inaccordance with section 70.
		“Asylum claim” has the meaning given by section 113(1) of the Nationality,Immigration and Asylum Act [2002 (c. 41)](/id/ukpga/2002/41?view=plain "Go toitem of legislation").
		A customs officer is a person commissioned by the Commissioners of Customsand Excise under section 6(3) of the Customs and Excise Management Act [1979(c. 2)](/id/ukpga/1979/2?view=plain "Go to item of legislation").
		“High Court” in relation to Scotland means the High Court of Justiciary.
		In relation to Scotland, references to an appeal being discontinued are tobe construed as references to its being abandoned.
		“Police officer” in relation to Northern Ireland has the same meaning asin the Police (Northern Ireland) Act [2000 (c.32)](/id/ukpga/2000/32?view=plain "Go to item of legislation").
		A provisional warrant is a warrant issued under section 73(3).
		A service policeman is a member of the Royal Navy Regulating Branch, theRoyal Marines Police, the Royal Military Police or the Royal Air Force Police.
		The Provost Marshal of the Royal Air Force and any officer appointed toexercise the functions conferred on provost officers by the Air Force Act 1955(3 & 4 Eliz. 2 c. 19) are to be taken to be members of the Royal Air ForcePolice for the purposes of subsection (13).
		This section and sections 213 to 215 apply for the purposes of this Act.
